06777nam a22008535i 9781479843145DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798431457 a10.18574/nyu/9781479843145.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547520  a(OCoLC)957157672  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0271102bisacsh04a355.2/9097322300aDrawdown :bThe American Way of Postwar /ced. by Jason W. Warren. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWarfare and Culture ;v800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The American Way of Postwar -- tPART I. BUILDING THE AMERICAN MILITARY IDEAL -- t1. The Art of War -- t2. Liberty Paradox -- t3. Surprisingly Professional -- tPART II. MANAGING INDUSTRIAL-ERA WARFARE -- t4. Challenged Competency -- t5. The Elusive Lesson -- t6. When the Smoke Clears -- tPART III. CONCEPTUALIZING COLD WAR FRAMEWORK -- t7. Searching for the Greatest Generation’s Army in 1950 -- t8. The Post–Korean War Drawdown under the Eisenhower Administration -- t9. Once Again with the High and Mighty -- tPART IV. SEARCHING FOR A NEW PARADIGM -- t10. Post-Vietnam Drawdown: The Myth of the Abrams Doctrine -- t11. The “Good” Drawdown -- t12. Preaching after the Devil’s Death -- tEpilogue -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnalyzes the cultural attitudes, political decisions, and institutions surrounding the maintenance of armed forces throughout American history While traditionally, Americans view expensive military structure as a poor investment and a threat to liberty, they also require a guarantee of that very freedom, necessitating the employment of armed forces. Beginning with the seventeenth-century wars of the English colonies, Americans typically increased their military capabilities at the beginning of conflicts only to decrease them at the apparent conclusion of hostilities. In Drawdown: The American Way of Postwar, a stellar team of military historians argue that the United States sometimes managed effective drawdowns, sowing the seeds of future victory that Americans eventually reaped. Yet at other times, the drawing down of military capabilities undermined our readiness and flexibility, leading to more costly wars and perhaps defeat. The political choice to reduce military capabilities is influenced by Anglo-American pecuniary decisions and traditional fears of government oppression, and it has been haphazard at best throughout American history. These two factors form the basic American “liberty dilemma,” the vexed relationship between the nation and its military apparatuses from the founding of the first colonies through to present times. With the termination of large-scale operations in Iraq and the winnowing of forces in Afghanistan, the United States military once again faces a significant drawdown in standing force structure and capabilities. The political and military debate currently raging around how best to affect this force reduction continues to lack a proper historical perspective. This volume aspires to inform this dialogue. Not a traditional military history, Drawdown analyzes cultural attitudes, political decisions, and institutions surrounding the maintenance of armed forces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / Military / United States.2bisacsh1 aBertinetti, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBissonnette, Ashley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonin, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClemi